% layout 'default', title => "About the Global Change Information System", fixed => 1;
<h2>
    <center>About the Global Change Information System</center>
</h2>

</p>
  The National Climate Assessment and Development Advisory Committee (NCADAC)
  recommended in 2013 that the NCA process “manage data to maximize utility and
  transparency.” The report also highlighted the importance of “developing a
  comprehensive web-based system to deploy and manage global change information
  and present it in a way that can be used by and benefit scientists, the
  public, and decision-makers.” To achieve these goals, the <a
  href="http://www.globalchange.gov/about">US Global Change Research
  Program</a> (USGCRP) established the Global Change Information System (GCIS).
  GCIS coordinates and integrates information about changes in the global
  environment and related societal effects, with a focus on Federal information
  products.
</p>
<p itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/WebApplication" itemprop="description">
  The GCIS, which continues to be managed and curated by USGCRP, is an
  open-source, web-based resource designed for use by scientists, decision
  makers, and the public. It links together a network of information, including
  organizations, datasets, and research, especially those products maintained
  and disseminated by government agencies and organizations. GCIS serves as a
  key access point to assessments, reports, and tools produced by the USGCRP –
  and the native data underpinning all of them. In addition, the GCIS guides
  users to global change research produced by the 13 USGCRP member agencies.
</p>

<h3>Global Change</h3>
<p>
  For the purposes of the GCIS, “global change” refers to changes in the global
  environment that may alter the capacity of the Earth to sustain life. Global
  change encompasses climate change, but it also includes other critical
  drivers of environmental change that may interact with climate change, such
  as land use change, the alteration of the water cycle, changes in
  biogeochemical cycles, and biodiversity loss.
</p>
<p>
  Global change information is structured using the
  <%= link_to 'resources' => begin %>GCIS data model<%= end %>; this data model
  represents relationships and entities such as reports, report chapters,
  figures, images, tables, bibliographic entries, organizations and people.
</p>

<h3>External Standards & Resources</h3>
<h4>Identifiers</h4>
<p>
  GCIS makes use of external identifiers such as <a href="https://www.doi.org/"
  target="_blank">Digital Object Identifiers (DOIs)</a>, <a
  href="https://orcid.org/" target="_blank">ORCIDs</a>, <a
  href="https://www.isbn-international.org/" target="_blank">ISBNs</a>, <a
  href="http://www.issn.org/" target="_blank">ISSNs</a>. ISBN resolution is
  handled through <a href="https://www.worldcat.org/"
  target="_blank">WorldCat</a>.  They may also utilize identifiers created for
  other aggregator systems, such as <a href="https://www.data.gov/"
  target="_blank">Data.gov</a> identifiers. When GCIS must create its own
  identifier, it may utilize a <a
  href="https://www.rfc-editor.org/rfc/rfc4122.txt" target="_blank">Universally
  Unique Identifiers (UUIDs)</a> when no human-readable identifier is
  reasonable.
</p>
<h4>Provenance</h4>
<p>
  GCIS utilizes <a href="https://www.w3.org/TR/prov-overview/"
  target="_blank">W3C provenance</a> to represent some relationships inside of
  GCIS. In particular, GCIS utilizes <a
  href="https://www.w3.org/TR/2013/REC-prov-o-20130430/"
  target="_blank">PROV-O</a> and <a href="http://purl.org/spar/cito"
  target="_blank">CiTO</a> verbs.
</p>
<h4>Technology</h4>
<p>
  GCIS is written in <a href="http://perl.org" target="_blank">Perl</a> using
  the <a href="http://mojolicio.us" target="_blank">Mojolicious</a> web
  framework, the <a href="https://metacpan.org/pod/Rose::DB"
  target="_blank">Rose::DB</a> Database interface, and many other fine modules
  from the <a href="http://metacpan.org" target="_blank">CPAN</a>. It relies on
  <a href="http://postgresql.org" target="_blank">PostgreSQL</a> for data
  storage.
</p>
<p>
  Map inserts are supported by <a href="https://www.openstreetmap.org/"
  target="_blank">OpenStreetMap</a> data with <a href="https://www.mapbox.com/"
  target="_blank">MapBox</a> tiles and implementation through <a
  href="https://leafletjs.com/" target="_blank">LeafletJS</a>.
</p>
<h4>Data Export Formats</h4>
<p>
  GCIS offers a multitude of human- and machine-readable data export formats,
  defaulting with the <a href="https://html.spec.whatwg.org/multipage/"
  target="_blank">HTML</a> pages. Publication pages can be downloaded as <a
  href="https://json.org/" target="_blank">JSON</a> and <a
  href="http://yaml.org/" target="_blank">YAML</a> data, the semantic formats
  <a href="http://www.w3.org/TR/turtle/" target="_blank">Turtle</a>, <a
  href="https://www.w3.org/TR/n-triples/" target="_blank">N-Triples</a>, <a
  href="https://www.w3.org/wiki/JSON_Triple_Sets" target="_blank">JSON
  Triples</a>, <a href="http://www.w3.org/TR/rdf-syntax-grammar/"
  target="_blank">RDF+XML</a>, and <a href="https://www.w3.org/TR/rdf-json/"
  target="_blank">RDF+JSON</a>, and visual representations in <a
  href="http://graphviz.org/" target="_blank">Graphiz</a>, and <a
  href="https://www.w3.org/Graphics/SVG/" target="_blank">SVG</a> of the
  semantic mapping.  Additionally, the data <%= link_to 'resources' => begin %>
  Array(s)<%= end %> behind <%= link_to 'resources' => begin %>Table<%= end
  %> Publications may be downloaded as <a
  href="https://tools.ietf.org/html/rfc4180" target="_blank">CSV</a>.  List
  pages can be downloaded as <a href="https://json.org/"
  target="_blank">JSON</a>, <a href="http://yaml.org/"
  target="_blank">YAML</a>, or <a href="https://tools.ietf.org/html/rfc4180"
  target="_blank">CSV</a> formatted data.
</p>

